===============================================================================
REFACTOR PLAN (next step, after user verification)
===============================================================================

For each Category A file:

  1. Wrap the existing struct-build at the end of the function with a
     `predictive_model(...)` constructor call:

         pmodel_obj = predictive_model(stats_struct);
         varargout{1} = pmodel_obj;    % or return as the primary output

     This is back-compatible because struct fields with matching property
     names are copied verbatim, and the constructor already does legacy
     translations for SVMModel/SVRModel and the
     classification_d_singleinterval / regression_d_singleinterval
     fields (per @predictive_model/predictive_model.m).

  2. Rename the in-function variable (S, STATS, STATS_FINAL,
     test_results, stats1, stats2) to `pmodel_obj` for the OUTPUT only;
     intermediate working structs can keep their names if heavy renaming
     would be churny.

  3. Update the help block:
       - change ":Outputs: S - Structure with ..." to "pmodel_obj -
         @predictive_model object with ..."
       - add a one-line note: "See @predictive_model for the full
         property list and method surface."
       - fix any typos noticed during the edit.

  4. Where the function takes the OUTPUT of another xval_ and operates
     on it (e.g. xval_lasso_brain calls xval_regression_multisubject),
     keep the inner call returning a predictive_model and adapt the
     outer code to read from object properties instead of struct fields.
     Touch the inner function FIRST so callers can rely on the new
     contract.

  5. Per the plan (Phase 0/1 not yet done), no fit/predict method
     calls happen here — these wrappers continue to run their own CV
     loops and bootstrap internally and just box up the result. The
     consolidation onto a single engine is Phase 2-3 work.

